{{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=14|marker=religious-shinto|frame-align=center|frame-width=200|coord={{coord|35|4|28.1|N|136|56|36.3|E}}}}
}}'''Narumi Hachiman Shrine'' (Narumi Hachimangu) is {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|WD=Q80434|1=Aichi Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Nagoya City|Q11751|WD=Q11751|1=Nagoya}}{{ill|lt=Midori Ward (Nagoya City)|Q1155209|WD=Q1155209|lt=Midori Ward|1=Midori-ku, Nagoya}}{{jalink|Narumi Town {{ill|lt=Shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}}{{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=8}} located in (Nagoya City)|Q136913130|Narumi Town}}. {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|WD=Q514506|1=Owari Province}}{{ill|lt=Aichi County (Aichi Prefecture)|Q552687|WD=Q552687|lt=Aichi District|1=Aichi District}} It is also said to be the Ronsha of ``{{ill|lt=Kawahara Shrine|Q3194327|WD=Q3194327|1=Kawahara Shrine}}'' and the ronsha of ``Izoe Shrine.''

=== Overview ===
It has been called "Hachiman" since ancient times, and was considered to be a separate shrine to {{ill|lt=Narumi Shrine|Q11495515|WD=Q11495515|1=Narumi Shrine}}. The location of the shrine was {{ill|lt=Edago|Q11533553|WD=Q11533553|1=Edago}} in {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Narumi Village|1=UNKNOWN}}, in the area that was called Zennoan Village in the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Edo period|1=Edo period|WD=Q184963}}. The year of its founding is unknown, but there are records of shrine occupations dating back to the {{ill|lt=Kamakura period|Q236205|WD=Q236205|1=Kamakura period}}, and a {{ill|lt=camphor tree|Q158722|WD=Q158722|1=Camphora officinarum}} that is over 1,000 years old remains within the precincts, suggesting that it may be an old shrine that dates back to before the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}}. As mentioned later, it is Shikinaisha's Ronsha.

Around this shrine, the remains of a village from the {{ill|lt=Yayoi period|Q207858|WD=Q207858|1=Yayoi period}}, ``Maenowa Ruins,'' have been discovered, and {{ill|lt=Yayoi pottery|Q11487461|WD=Q11487461|1=Yayoi pottery}} have been unearthed.

=== Enshrined God ===
* {{ill|lt=Emperor Ojin|Q317997|WD=Q317997|1=Emperor Ōjin}} (Shinada Wake no Mikoto) {{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=3}}
* {{ill|lt=Empress Jingu|Q232803|WD=Q232803|1=Empress Jingū}} (Senagatai Hibi no Mikoto) {{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=3}}
* {{ill|lt=Tamayoribime (Hyuga mythology)|Q3082751|WD=Q3082751|lt=Tamayoribibimei|1=Tamayori-hime (mother of Jimmu)}}{{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=3}}
* {{ill|lt=Ninigi|Q1056017|WD=Q1056017|lt=Nishi Geishi|1=Ninigi-no-Mikoto}}{{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=3}}
* {{ill|WD=Q595520|lt=Tsukuyomi|Q595520|WD=Q595520|lt=Tsukiyomi|1=Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto}}{{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=3}}

=== History ===
The company seems to have already existed in the Kamakura period, and there is a record that Motohisa Oga, the first generation member of the Kuno family, became a company official in the first year of {{ill|lt=Sadanaga|Q1194168|WD=Q1194168|1=Jōei}} ({{ill|lt=1232|Q5418|WD=Q5418|1=1232}}). Since ancient times, it has been called ``Hachimangu Shrine'' and was treated as a companion to Narumi Togu Shrine (Narumi Shrine). {{ill|lt=Sengoku period (Japan)|Q204023|WD=Q204023|lt=During the Warring States period|1=Sengoku period}}, there is a record that {{ill|lt=Yoshimoto Imagawa|Q1054305|WD=Q1054305|1=Imagawa Yoshimoto}} and {{ill|lt=Shigemasa Yamaguchi|Q11467507|WD=Q11467507|lt=Chōjiro Shigemasa|1=Yamaguchi Shigemasa}} {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=corporate territory|1=UNKNOWN}} was {{ill|lt=donated|Q11455717|WD=Q11455717|1=contribution}} to our company and Narumi Togu Shrine.

According to ``{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Owari Makiyōki|1=UNKNOWN}},'' the priest Mr. Kuno submitted a document stating that Narumi Hachimangu Shrine is ``Kawahara Shrine,'' Aichi District, Owari Province, in ``{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}.'' According to ``{{ill|lt=Specially Selected Names of Gods|Q11571092|WD=Q11571092|1=Tokusen Jinmyōchō}}'', there are some Edo-era fishing lanterns and {{ill|lt=ridge tags|Q8008834|WD=Q8008834|1=Munafuda}} that have the words ``Kawahara Shrine'' written on them.On the other hand, there is a theory that it corresponds to "Izoe Shrine" in Aichi District, Owari Province, but according to Kunihiko Sakakibara, a {{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=4}}{{Sfn|Sakakibara|2020|pp=64}}{{Efn|{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=local historian|1=UNKNOWN}}, Izoe Shrine was built during the Heian period. When it was abolished in the late period, Atsuta Daiguji disowned Hachimangu Shrine, and during the Oei era ({{ill|lt=1394|Q6398|WD=Q6398|1=1394}} to {{ill|lt=1428|Q6315|WD=Q6315|1=1428}}), the enshrinement site of Izoe Shrine, which had been abolished, was renamed to the old Jizoyama ({{jalink|Narumi Town) (Nagoya City)|Q136913130|Q136913130|Q136913130|Komatsuyama, Narumi Town), it is said to have been rebuilt as a Hachimangu Shrine in the former Tange (Kiyomizu Temple, Narumi Town). It is said that in the early Muromachi period, it was moved from that place to the present-day Azazenowa area, which was at the mouth of the {{ill|lt=Ogigawa|Q11496839|WD=Q11496839|lt=Kurosuegawa|1=Ōgi River}} large camphor tree. n|Sakakibara|2000|pp=88}}{{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=5}}{{Sfn|Sakakibara|2020|pp=64}}{{Sfn|Sakakibara|1984|pp=103}}. Izoe Shrine was later enshrined as Kitanosha, a subsidiary shrine of Hachimangu Shrine, but it is said to have been abolished in the Edo period {{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=5}}. }}, from the description in ``{{ill|lt=Owari Province Fudoki|Q135598023|WD=Q135598023|1=Owari no Kuni Fudoki}}'', it is presumed that Izoe Shrine was located in Aichi District {{ill|lt=Aichi County (Aichi Prefecture) #Go|Q552687|WD=Q552687|lt=Hibego|1=Aichi District}}, and it is unreasonable to compare our company with Izoe Shrine.In {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|WD=Q1325001|1=Genroku}}3 ({{ill|lt=1690|Q7678|WD=Q7678|1=1690}}), he served as a priest at Narumi Shrine along with the Makino family.{{ill|lt=Narumi-juku|Q3033344|WD=Q3033344|1=Narumi-juku}}The Kuno family of Honmachi moved to Maenowa and served as a priest.{{Sfn|Awakawa|2013|pp=47}}{{Sfn|Awakawa|2013|pp=48}}. In {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|WD=Q1325001|1=Genroku}}13 ({{ill|lt=1700|Q6813|WD=Q6813|1=1700}}), the Makino family priests and the Kuno family priests quarreled and the festival was divided. The parishioners from Sakumachi to Nakajima changed from those of Narumi Shrine to those of Hachimangu Shrine, and the festival began to be held in front and behind the scenes {{Sfn|Awakawa|2013|pp=48}}. In recent years, efforts have been seen to bring together the front and back sides of the festival and gather floats at Narumi-juku Honmachi.{{Sfn|Awakawa|2013|pp=35}}

=== Chronology ===
* {{ill|lt=Koji (Japan)|Q1143910|WD=Q1143910|lt=Koji|1=Kōji (Muromachi period)}} December 3, 17 ({{ill|lt=1557|Q6595|WD=Q6595|1=1557}}) - Yoshimoto Imagawa donates Kanda 11 kan 50 mon to Hachiman Shrine and Narumi Togu (Narumi Shrine) {{Sfn|Awakawa|2013|pp=47}}.
* {{ill|lt=Tensho|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 17th year ({{ill|lt=1589|Q6759|WD=Q6759|1=1589}}) - Chojiro Shigemasa Yamaguchi donated 20 kanmon of shrine territory to the priests of both Hachimangu and Narumi Togu shrines.{{Sfn|Awakawa|2013|pp=47}}.
* {{ill|lt=Genna (Japan)|Q635245|WD=Q635245|lt=Genna|1=Genna}} August 8 ({{ill|lt=1622|Q6815|WD=Q6815|1=1622}}) - Reconstruction of the main shrine {{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=4}}.
* {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|WD=Q1325001|1=Genroku}}13 ({{ill|lt=1700|Q6813|WD=Q6813|1=1700}}) - As a result of an argument between the Makino family priests and the Kuno family priests, the parishioners from Sakumachi to Nakajima changed from those of Narumi Shrine to those of Hachimangu Shrine, and the festival began to be held in front and behind the scenes {{Sfn|Awakawa|2013|pp=48}}.
* {{ill|lt=Culture|Q11042|WD=Q11042|1=Culture}} 1st year ({{ill|lt=1804|Q6894|WD=Q6894|1=1804}}) - Constructed a water fountain using trees in the temple grounds {{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=14}}.
* {{ill|lt=Bunsei|Q1327119|WD=Q1327119|1=Bunsei}}2nd year ({{ill|lt=1819|Q6967|WD=Q6967|1=1819}}) - Rebuild the Chozuya.{{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=14}}.* Bunsei 12 ({{ill|lt=1819|Q6967|WD=Q6967|1=1819}}) - Rebuild the worship hall, watariden, etc.{{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=14}}.
* {{ill|lt=Kyoho|Q1145048|WD=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}}18 ({{ill|lt=1733|Q6972|WD=Q6972|1=1733}}) November 1st - {{ill|lt=Owari Domain|Q1062072|WD=Q1062072|1=Owari Domain}} Lord {{ill|lt=Muneharu Tokugawa|Q6636871|WD=Q6636871|1=Tokugawa Muneharu}} visits Narumi Hachimangu Shrine {{Sfn|Sakakibara|2000|pp=88}}.
* August 19, 4th year of {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Yasunaga|1=UNKNOWN}} ({{ill|lt=1775|Q7700|WD=Q7700|1=1775}}) - {{ill|lt=Owari Domain|Q1062072|WD=Q1062072|1=Owari Domain}} lord {{ill|lt=Muneharu Tokugawa|Q6636871|WD=Q6636871|1=Tokugawa Muneharu}} visits Narumi Hachiman Shrine {{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=34}}.
* {{ill|lt=Original|Q1145754|WD=Q1145754|1=Genbun}}2nd year ({{ill|lt=1737|Q6993|WD=Q6993|1=1737}}) - Otabisho was built on the banks of the Ogi River{{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=15}}.
* {{ill|lt=Ansei|Q1327259|WD=Q1327259|1=Ansei}}6 ({{ill|lt=1859|Q7687|WD=Q7687|1=1859}}) - Torii was rebuilt{{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=15}}.
* July 28, {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}}) - Promoted to {{ill|lt=Modern company rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=Village company|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}. The name of the shrine was changed from Hachiman-sha to Hachiman-gu {{Sfn|Sakakibara|2000|pp=89}}.* Meiji 13 ({{ill|lt=1880|Q7806|WD=Q7806|1=1880}}) - Construction of the shrine building {{Sfn|Sakakibara|2004|pp=14}}.
