=== Festival ===
In the past, the festival was held throughout the town on the same day as {{ill|lt=Narumi Shrine|Q11495515|WD=Q11495515|1=Narumi Shrine}}, which is also located in Narumi, but in {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|WD=Q1325001|1=Genroku}}13 ({{jalink |1700|Q6813}}), a dispute arose between the two shrines, and since then the festival has been divided into front (Narumi Hachiman Shrine) and back (Narumi Shrine) {{Sfn|Awakawa|2013|pp=34}}. In recent years, there have been efforts to unite the front and back sides and gather floats in Narumi-juku Honmachi, and the festival is now being held as before the festival was divided.{{Sfn|Awakawa|2013|pp=35}}

The Narumi Hachiman Shrine annual festival (Omote Festival) used to be held on August 15th, but since the first year of the Taisho era ({{ill|lt=1912|Q2077|WD=Q2077|1=1912}}) it has been held on {{ill|lt=September 15th|Q2846|WD=Q2846|1=September 15}}, and since the Showa era it has been held on {{ill|lt=October 15th|Q2919|WD=Q2919|1=October 15}}. In recent years, the annual festival day has been set on a Saturday in the first half of {{ill|lt=October|Q124|WD=Q124|1=October}}{{Sfn|Sakakibara|2005|pp=26}}.

At the Shōjo Festival, a giant doll called {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=shōjō|1=UNKNOWN}} made of a bamboo framework with a red face mask and upper half of the body covered with a costume appears, and there is the ``Narumi Hachiman Shrine Reitaisai Festival'' (Omote Festival), where adults wear shōjō dolls and chase children around. Shōto is the deity of Narumi Hachimangu Shrine. The monkeys hit children with fake hands and sticks, and it is said that children who are hit by the monkeys do not get sick.{{Sfn|Awakawa|2013|pp=35}}.

